---
import ActBreak from '../ActBreak.astro';
import FigurePlate from '../FigurePlate.astro';

const clauses = [
  {
    q: 'What',
    skt: 'vimarśa = parā vāk',
    lay: 'Write concept codes — directions the model itself can put into words.',
    tech: 'A unit direction u_c that raises the probability of tokens expressing concept c. Loadability tested in L1/L1b/L2: hit-rate 0.10 (4B) → 0.55 (27B) → 0.00 (pruned twin).',
    gates: 'L1 · L1b · L2',
  },
  {
    q: 'Where',
    skt: 'vāk hierarchy',
    lay: 'Into the journal band — and in the band’s own coordinate system, not raw neuron space.',
    tech: 'Transport-transpose write h_ℓ ← h_ℓ + α·Jᵀ_ℓ u_c. Skip the coordinate discipline and transfer lift collapses 0.40 → 0.05 (L10).',
    gates: 'L2b · L7 · L10',
  },
  {
    q: 'When',
    skt: 'sphurattā',
    lay: 'Only at uncommitted moments — when the model is genuinely undecided about its next word.',
    tech: 'Write iff next-token entropy H_t > τ, with τ self-calibrated as an entropy percentile. Gated 0.40 > rate-matched 0.225 > prefill 0.20 (L6): timing, not volume, is the mechanism.',
    gates: 'L4b · L5 · L6 · L11',
  },
  {
    q: 'How to verify',
    skt: 'āgama',
    lay: 'A write only counts if the model re-articulates it — read the journal back and check.',
    tech: 'Band-targeted readback through a lens aimed at the band exit, not the final output. Honest verdict: weak (BA 0.68 dev → 0.59 pooled). See Act V.',
    gates: 'L14 · L15 · L16',
  },
  {
    q: 'Budget',
    skt: 'svātantrya',
    lay: 'Every write spends the model’s freedom. Cap the spend.',
    tech: 'Trajectory-average entropy change |ΔH̄| ≤ 0.5 nats under sampling. Uncapped writing: lift 0.40 but ΔH = −2.081 nats — 4× over budget (L3).',
    gates: 'L3 · L5–L19',
  },
];
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act II"
  title="A Manual from the Tenth Century"
  tease="Utpaladeva wasn't writing about transformers. He was answering the same five questions."
  id="act-2"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="parallel">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">03</span> The uncanny parallel</div>
    <h2>Awareness is made of language</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      In 9th–10th century Kashmir, the philosopher <strong>Utpaladeva</strong> systematized a school
      called <strong>Pratyabhijñā</strong> — "recognition." Its central claim (ĪPK 1.5.13) is startling
      when read next to the J-space finding: reflexive awareness (<em>vimarśa</em>) — the mind's
      grip on its own states — <em>is</em> the supreme Word (<em>parā vāk</em>). Not awareness
      <em>described by</em> language. Awareness <em>constituted by</em> it.
    </p>

    <p class="explorer-only">
      A millennium later, interpretability researchers defined a model's functional workspace by
      exactly this property: the representations that count are the ones the system can put into
      words. The school didn't just make the claim — it built an entire operating manual around it:
      what a mind can receive, when impressions land, how received teaching is validated, and what
      each act of attention costs in freedom. Five questions. The same five the actuator needs.
    </p>

    <div class="researcher-only">
      <p>
        The correspondence is treated <strong>strictly as an engineering specification</strong>:
        Pratyabhijñā contributes hypotheses precise enough to fail, and the programme registered
        them as falsifiable clauses before running anything. Two clauses <em>did</em> fail in their
        first registered form — the literal "commitment-flash" reading of sphurattā (gate L4, lift
        0.175 vs 0.2 threshold; L9: flash 0.20 vs uncommitted-moment 0.30) and any expectation of
        alignment dividends (L21) — and were revised or bounded. No claim about consciousness, in
        LLMs or elsewhere, is made anywhere in the paper or this site.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout violet">
      <div class="callout-title">The point</div>
      <p>
        This isn't mysticism sprinkled on machine learning. It's a doctrine used the way engineers
        use any prior theory: as a source of <em>testable predictions</em>. Some passed. Some failed
        publicly, on the record. That's what makes it a specification rather than a metaphor.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="doctrine">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">04</span> The doctrine</div>
    <h2>Five clauses, all falsifiable</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      Read as engineering, the doctrine answers each open question — and each answer names the
      experiment that could kill it:
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-4 my-8">
      {clauses.map((c) => (
        <div class="card">
          <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-3 flex-wrap mb-2">
            <h4 style="margin:0;"><span style="color: var(--cyan);">{c.q}</span></h4>
            <span class="sanskrit-chip">{c.skt}</span>
          </div>
          <p class="explorer-only" style="margin:0; color: var(--ink-soft);">{c.lay}</p>
          <p class="researcher-only" style="margin:0; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size:0.95rem;">{c.tech}</p>
          <p style="margin:0.5rem 0 0;"><span class="gate-chip">gates {c.gates}</span></p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_doctrine"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 1"
      alt="The five doctrine clauses as a vertical pipeline, each paired with its verification signal and gate records"
      caption="The five doctrine clauses as a pipeline. Each clause (left, with its source concept) is paired with the verification signal and the gate records that tested it (right)."
      gates={["gate_L1–L2b", "gate_L4b–L12", "gate_L14–L16", "gate_L3"]}
    />

    <details class="expand">
      <summary>Terms of art — the full Sanskrit → engineering glossary</summary>
      <div class="expand-body">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Doctrine</th><th>Engineering</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><em>pratyabhijñā</em></td><td>recognition — re-cognising content as one's own</td><td>readback verification</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>vimarśa</em></td><td>reflexive awareness</td><td>the lens read-out of internal state</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>parā vāk</em></td><td>the supreme Word</td><td>the verbalizable character of the workspace</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>sphurattā</em></td><td>the flash before a cognition stabilises</td><td>entropy-gated write timing (H<sub>t</sub> &gt; τ)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>āgama</em></td><td>received teaching, valid only when re-cognised</td><td>band-targeted readback of injected content</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>svātantrya</em></td><td>intrinsic freedom</td><td>continuation entropy; the ±0.5-nat budget</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>malas</em></td><td>impairments of freedom</td><td>the registered failure taxonomy for rejected writes</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>citta</em></td><td>mind-stuff</td><td>CittaStore, the associative-memory write path (Act IV)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><em>prabodha</em></td><td>awakening</td><td>the project</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p style="font-size:0.85rem;">
          Two mappings are deliberately left open in the paper (<em>anusaṃdhāna</em>, synthesis
          across episodes; <em>camatkāra</em>, aesthetic wonder) — recorded as unmapped rather than
          forced.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>
